payload.user_prompt:
Propose 4 distinct strategies to beat the baseline.

PROBLEM: Euclidean TSP on the TSPLIB95 benchmark (known optima). The solver is run on several dev instances; score = mean gap %% above the known optimum (lower is better, 0 = optimal on every instance). Distances use the TSPLIB metric: each edge rounded to the nearest integer. The winning solver is re-evaluated on held-out instances at the end.
INSTANCE: TSPLIB95 dev set: berlin52 (52 cities), st70 (70 cities), eil76 (76 cities), kroA100 (100 cities), rd100 (100 cities). Optima are known; score is the mean gap %% above optimum across all dev instances (TSPLIB rounded-integer metric). 6 held-out instances are kept hidden for final verification.
SCOPE: {"objective": "Minimize the mean gap percentage above the known TSPLIB95 optima across five dev instances (berlin52, st70, eil76, kroA100, rd100) by developing a TSP solver that outperforms the nearest-neighbor + 2-opt baseline of 6.59% mean gap.", "success_criteria": {"target_improvement_pct": 18.0, "rationale": "An 18% improvement over the 6.59% baseline corresponds to achieving a mean gap of approximately 5.40% or below. For instances of this size (52\u2013100 cities), well-implemented 3-opt or Lin-Kernighan style moves combined with better initial solutions (e.g., greedy or savings-based construction) routinely achieve gaps under 2-3% at optimum, making 5.4% a realistic and meaningful target within the 10s/experiment and 5-round constraints. The operator-suggested 18% improvement aligns with what is achievable by augmenting 2-opt with 3-opt or Or-opt moves without requiring full LKH-level sophistication."}, "constraints": ["Maximum 5 optimization rounds", "Budget cap of $2 USD total", "Maximum 10 seconds wall-clock time per experiment run", "Must use TSPLIB95 rounded-integer edge distances (nint(euclidean) metric) for all evaluations", "Solver must be deterministic or produce reproducible results to enable fair comparison", "No external TSP solver binaries (e.g., Concorde, LKH) may be called; algorithm must be implemented directly", "Score is mean gap % across all five dev instances; no single-instance overfitting"], "stop_conditions": ["Mean gap % reaches 5.40% or below (18% improvement over 6.59% baseline)", "All 5 optimization rounds are exhausted", "Total spend reaches $2.00 USD", "Mean gap % reaches 0.5% or below (near-optimal, no further improvement warranted)", "Two consecutive rounds produce less than 0.05 percentage-point improvement in mean gap"], "reasoning": "For Euclidean TSP instances with 52\u2013100 cities, nearest-neighbor + 2-opt is a reasonable but not strong baseline. Standard enhancements\u2014such as greedy or savings-based construction, Or-opt (1-, 2-, 3-city relocations), and 3-opt moves\u2014can typically halve the gap versus 2-opt alone on instances this small, often achieving 1-3% gaps. The 10-second time limit is generous for instances under 100 cities, allowing multiple restarts or perturbation strategies (e.g., random restarts with 2-opt, or Lin-Kernighan style moves). The 18% improvement target (reaching ~5.4% mean gap) is conservative relative to what the algorithm class can achieve, providing a realistic success threshold within 5 rounds. More aggressive targets (e.g., <2% gap) would likely require LKH-style implementations that are complex to develop in few rounds, so 18% balances ambition with achievability."}

Each strategy must be implementable in pure Python within the time limit.
Return JSON:
{
  "hypotheses": [
    {"name": "<short name>", "strategy": "<algorithm family>",
      "hypothesis": "<falsifiable claim: doing X will improve over baseline because Y>",
      "risk": "<main reason this could fail>"}
  ]
}

