      "name": "Multi-restart 2-opt with Random Perturbation",
      "strategy": "Iterated Local Search with random restarts",
      "hypothesis": "Running nearest-neighbor construction from multiple random starting cities, applying full 2-opt to each, and keeping the best solution will beat the single-start baseline below 5.4% mean gap, because the 52-100 city instances are small enough to complete 10-20 restarts within 10 seconds and diversity in starting tours prevents convergence to a single poor local optimum.",
      "risk": "All random restarts may converge to similar local optima if the 2-opt landscape has few basins of attraction, yielding diminishing returns; the time budget may also be tighter than expected if 2-opt is slow in pure Python."
    },
    {
      "name": "Lin-Kernighan Style 3-opt",
      "strategy": "3-opt local search with neighbor lists",
      "hypothesis": "Implementing sequential 3-opt moves (examining all triple-edge exchanges) with a candidate neighbor list restricted to the 10 nearest neighbors per city will achieve a mean gap below 3% because 3-opt can escape 2-opt local optima and the neighbor-list restriction keeps complexity manageable within 10 seconds for instances under 100 cities.",
      "risk": "Pure Python 3-opt over all city triples is O(n^3) per pass and may be too slow even with neighbor lists; incorrect segment reversal logic in 3-opt reconnection cases is a common implementation bug that could produce invalid tours."
    },
    {
      "name": "Iterated Or-opt with Double-Bridge Perturbation",
      "strategy": "Iterated Local Search with double-bridge kick",
      "hypothesis": "Alternating between full Or-opt local search and a double-bridge perturbation (a 4-opt move that splits the tour into 4 segments and reconnects them in a different order) will achieve a mean gap below 4% because double-bridge moves are non-sequential and escape all 2-opt and 3-opt local optima, and the small instance sizes allow many ILS iterations within 10 seconds, enabling broad exploration of the tour space.",
      "risk": "Double-bridge perturbation is random and may occasionally produce very poor tours that waste ILS iterations; without a good acceptance criterion the algorithm may not reliably improve over a well-tuned Or-opt run alone."
    }
  ]
}
